1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,000
I know zero Japanese, so MA never starts with an empty conversation.

2
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:25,000
English is the default for judges, and I can switch the whole lesson to Spanish.

3
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:39,000
Before I hear Japanese, I see the phrase, romaji, meaning, and exact task.

4
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:51,000
One tap plays a short model. Recording never starts by itself.

5
00:00:51,000 --> 00:01:06,000
I choose when to record, say the phrase once, and tap Finish and review.

6
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:23,000
GPT Realtime supplies the approximate transcript; MA validates it and shows one useful adjustment.

7
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:36,000
There is no pronunciation score. I retry the same visible phrase or continue.

8
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:53,000
Before the waiter speaks, MA explains the question, meaning, and what I should answer.

9
00:01:53,000 --> 00:02:07,000
The waiter turn is short, captioned, and deliberately non-overlapping.

10
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:24,000
I respond explicitly, and MA reviews my second voice turn before completion.

11
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Completing the exchange is not a score or a claim of mastery.

12
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:49,000
My audio goes directly to OpenAI for Realtime review and is not saved by the app.

13
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:56,000
The optional GPT-5.6 planner receives only structured lesson aggregates.

14
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:59,000
MA turns frontier voice technology into an actual first lesson.
